:: StoryInit
/* Scenario metadata
   SCENARIO TITLE:      One Eighty
   AUDIENCE:            Pilot (GA, 500-1,000 hr; protagonist 620 TT, private
                        ASEL, NO instrument rating, 3.2 hrs simulated
                        instrument, all of it years ago)
   TONE:                Professional
   PRIMARY TOPIC:       VFR into deteriorating weather and inadvertent IMC:
                        the 180 as a system, the confession call, and
                        surviving the white room you swore you'd never enter
   SECONDARY TOPIC:     Ridge-and-valley weather traps; get-there-itis with
                        a happy occasion attached; the get-under instinct
   AIRCRAFT/EQUIPMENT:  1981 Piper Warrior II (PA-28-161), N3389K. O-320,
                        160 hp. Six-pack, GNS 430W, KX 155, NO autopilot.
                        Club airplane, well kept, honest.
   SETTING:             KUNV State College PA to KLBE Latrobe (Arnold Palmer
                        Rgnl), about 80 nm southwest across the ridge-and-
                        valley Alleghenies. Saturday afternoon, mid-October.
                        A college reunion dinner at Coop's place near Latrobe.
   WEATHER:             Marginal VFR going worse where it matters: valleys
                        3,500-4,000 broken in haze, the Allegheny Front and
                        Laurel Highlands wearing the cloud bases, Johnstown
                        (on the plateau) already IFR, an old occlusion
                        draped on the high ground and a genuine improvement
                        coming from the west that is slower than forecast.
   ADM THEMES:          The early 180 vs. the late one; confession to ATC as
                        the counterintuitive save; the get-under trap;
                        conflicting forecast vs. observation; spatial
                        disorientation as physiology, not character
   HAZARDOUS ATTITUDES: Get-there-itis dressed as loyalty (Coop's dinner),
                        invulnerability (620 hours of good weather),
                        impulsivity (duck under, it's right there),
                        macho (needing no help from Approach)
   TOTAL DECISIONS:     Branching; every path passes 4+ decision points
   TOTAL ENDINGS:       8 (friction-win scrub 1, success/turnback 2,
                        qualified 2, scare 2, fatal 1)
   MIN DECISION DEPTH:  4
   TIMED DECISIONS:     No
   ESTIMATED DURATION:  20-30 minutes
   VERSION:             1.0
   LAST REVIEWED:       2026-07-07
   REVIEWER:            Claude (initial draft) / Harvey Madison (pending)

   Facts verified July 2026 (aviation MCP get_airport_info): KUNV twr,
   D-ATIS 127.65, LCL 128.475, rwy 06/24 6701x150, elev 1,230. KAOO no twr,
   rwys 03/21 5465x100 and 12/30 3668x75, elev 1,503. KJST twr, ATIS
   118.325, LCL 125.75, rwys 15/33 7004x150 and 05/23 4387x100, elev 2,284
   (plateau). KLBE twr, ATIS 118.375, LCL 125.0, rwy 06/24 8222x150, elev
   1,199. Route ~80 nm, TC ~245. Terrain: Bald Eagle ridge SE of KUNV, the
   Allegheny Front stepping up to the 2,300-2,900 plateau west of Altoona,
   Laurel Hill and Chestnut Ridge before the Latrobe valley.
*/
<<set $pathArray to []>>
<<set $badchoices to 0>>
<<set $readWeather to false>>
<<set $readRoute to false>>
<<set $readAircraft to false>>
<<set $readEscape to false>>
<<set $gates to false>>       /* briefed hard personal gates out loud */
<<set $delayed to false>>     /* took the 90-minute delay for improvement */
<<set $onTop to false>>       /* climbed above a broken layer */
<<set $inIMC to false>>       /* the white room */
<<set $confessed to false>>   /* told ATC the whole truth */
<<set $panic to 0>>           /* disorientation load, 0-3 */
<<set $probes to 0>>          /* one-more-valley probes flown */
<<set $divert to "">>         /* "", "KAOO", "KUNV", "grass" */

