:: End_KAOO_Wait [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the courtesy car"])>>

The courtesy car is a Crown Victoria of indeterminate vintage that smells like every FBO in America, and it eats the last fifty-five miles in an hour and five minutes of two-lane. You walk into Coop's at 9:20 to a cheer entirely disproportionate to the achievement, and the Warrior spends a quiet night chocked at Altoona, flying home tomorrow in Sunday's promised blue.

<<if $inIMC or $panic gte 2>>Late that night, on Coop's porch with the party warm behind you, you tell him the whole afternoon, including the part your logbook will summarize as "diverted for weather." He listens the way old friends listen and says, finally: "So the airplane's fine, you're fine, and you're here. Sounds like you passed."<</if>>

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The flight ended at the fence and the trip continued by Crown Victoria, which is what fences and courtesy cars are for. The airplane sleeps at a real airport, the pilot sleeps at the destination, and tomorrow's flying happens in tomorrow's weather.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The half-flight is an underrated instrument. Altoona banked twenty-five of the eighty miles, converted the remaining fifty-five into ground transportation, and did it all while every option was still open. <<if $inIMC or $panic gte 2>>On this particular path, the fence arrived after the wall had already taught its lesson up close; the honest debrief is that the ground option should have been exercised one decision sooner, and the porch version told to Coop is the version to remember.<<else>>Taken at the fence, on the gates as briefed, this is the system working exactly as designed: the decision was made at the kitchen table and merely executed in the air.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Building the trip out of exchangeable parts: fly what's flyable, drive what isn't, and refuse to let the airplane's location dictate the humans' evening. Also, tip whoever keeps the courtesy car's tank full. That car is safety equipment.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A divert isn't the end of the trip; it's a change of vehicle. The mission is the dinner, never the logbook entry.</p>
</div>
