:: End_Home_Low [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: eighteen careful miles"])>>

The eighteen miles home are flown at three thousand feet with the lid just overhead and your attention distributed like a security detail: terrain, towers, the hole's ghost behind you, the ATIS ahead. State College tower clears you to land in a voice that has no idea, and the tie-down chains go on with your hands still carrying a fine vibration that isn't the airplane's.

You sit in the parked Warrior for a while. Then you text Coop the only version that's true: "Not tonight. Long story. Telling it tomorrow with pancakes."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The on-top gamble ended with a closing hole, a spiraling descent through it, and eighteen chastened miles home under a low lid. Nothing was bent. Everything was spent: the margin, the daylight, and whatever remained of the theory that a VFR pilot can out-plan an undercast.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>VFR-on-top of a broken layer is a loan against the layer's future behavior, and broken layers over ridge country in a stalled occlusion default on that loan routinely. The decision that made this ending survivable was taking the hole immediately upon finding it, while it was still a hole: five more minutes of hunting a better one and this becomes a different ending. The descent itself (steep, spiraling, inside shrinking walls) is a maneuver with no margin for the leans, flown by a pilot with no instrument proficiency, and it worked because the ground stayed visible. That is one card off the top of the deck.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>The confession, from on top, while cruising in smooth clear air with full tanks: that phone-a-friend converts the entire problem into a radar service. It was available the whole time. The hole was luck; the radio was a plan, and the difference between those two words is this scenario's entire syllabus.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>On top of a closing layer, the best hole is a frequency. Spend luck only after the plan runs out.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
