:: End_Grass [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: the pasture"])>>

You fly it like a soft-field landing because it is one: full flaps, minimum speed, the fence at the near end cleared by a comfortable margin, the upslope doing half your braking. The Warrior rolls out in wet grass and stops in four hundred feet, intact, ticking, surrounded by mist and the profound indifference of eleven Angus cattle.

The farmer arrives by side-by-side inside ten minutes, and his opening line enters family legend immediately: "Y'all picked the good field. The other one's got the bull." The sheriff's deputy who follows is mostly curious. The FAA, when you self-report Monday, is businesslike and, on the facts (deteriorating weather, precautionary landing, no damage, no injuries), closes it with a phone call. The Warrior flies out of the pasture two mornings later, light and alone, off two thousand feet of dew-slick grass into a blue sky.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Caught between a cloud deck and a plateau with two hundred feet of clear air, you spent your remaining control on the best available surface instead of hunting for a better future. The airplane is unbent. The story has cattle in it. This is what winning looks like once the earlier doors have closed.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The precautionary landing is the most under-taught save in general aviation, and the reason is cultural, not technical: it feels like failure, reads like a headline, and requires admitting aloud that the plan is dead. Measure it instead against its actual alternatives at that moment: a blind climb into cloud on four-year-old instrument skills, or a two-hundred-foot crawl into terrain doing a hundred knots. Against those, a controlled arrival in a chosen field is not the consolation prize. It is the podium.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Earlier doors, obviously, and this scenario is full of them. But inside the last room: exactly this. Fly the machine to a full stop on the best surface in reach, favor control over distance, and let the paperwork be tomorrow's problem, because the paperwork for a precautionary landing is a conversation, and the paperwork for the alternatives is a docket. The insurance company would rather buy the farmer a fence. Ask them.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A field you chose beats any sky you didn't. Land the airplane while it's still yours to land.</p>
</div>
