:: End_Confess_Vectors [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: talked down, walked away"])>>

The FBO at Altoona produces coffee and a landline feel even though everything is cellular now. Approach's supervisor calls to check on you, which is a thing they do and nobody believes until it happens. There is no violation, no certificate action, no dragging before anyone: there is a suggestion, gently made, that an instrument instructor would enjoy meeting you, and a request to file the ASRS report, which you do that night in Coop's guest room with the party's last laughter coming through the floor and every detail still burned in.

The courtesy car made the dinner, barely. You made the dinner. That sentence took help.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>A VFR pilot <<if $onTop>>trapped on top<<else>>in cloud over rising terrain<</if>> said the true sentence into the radio, and the system built for exactly that sentence did exactly its job: radar, terrain awareness, a calm voice metering out one instruction at a time, and a vector to the side of the weather with a runway under it. Twenty minutes of borrowed competence, repaid in full at the tie-downs.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Run the accounting on the confession honestly, because pilot culture keeps the books wrong. Cost: saying "I need help" on a recorded frequency, and a bruise to the ego that healed by dinner. Return: an extra crew member with a God's-eye view, terrain separation you could not provide yourself, and structure (headings, altitudes, readbacks) that is itself an anti-panic instrument: the leans lose their vote when someone keeps handing your scan a next task. The pilots who die in this scenario's fatal branch almost all had this frequency available and unkeyed. <<if $panic gte 2>>The confession came late on this path, after the situation had already taxed the account. Late beats never by exactly one lifetime.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Making the call one branch earlier, from clear air, when it would have been a request instead of a rescue. And afterward: the ASRS report, the instructor's phone number actually dialed, and the story told straight at the table, because hangar honesty is how one pilot's Tuesday becomes another pilot's checklist.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>"I need help" is a complete sentence and the best one in the AIM. The frequency can't hear pride. It can only hear words.</p>
</div>
