:: End_LBE_Squeaked [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: through the keyhole"])>>

The plateau finally tilts down, the mist lifts a grudging hundred feet at a time, and the Latrobe valley opens ahead exactly as promised: scattered clouds, ten miles, a tower voice, an enormous lit runway. You land at 6:40, tie down with hands that need two tries per knot, and walk into Coop's at 7:15 to a hero's welcome for a flight that was twenty feet and one powerline from being none of this.

The dinner is wonderful. You are quieter than usual, and only you know the exchange rate.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The duck-under worked. That sentence, complete and true, is the most dangerous artifact this flight produced, because it will file itself in memory as evidence. The wires were cleared blind. The plateau crawl at four hundred feet threaded turbines in mist. Every card came off the top of the deck, and the deck owed you nothing.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Outcome bias has a specific mechanism worth naming: the memory of fear fades faster than the memory of success, so surviving a terrible bet quietly raises the odds you'll accept the next one. Tonight's data point, honestly labeled, reads: pressed into a closing notch, escaped a powerline by an unknowable margin, and continued at an altitude and visibility that removed every remaining option except perfection. The FAA's accident files hold hundreds of flights identical to this one through the final decision, differing only in the last variable, which was never under anyone's control.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Nothing after the notch, because after the notch there were no good options, only degrees of exposure: that is what "behind the airplane" means at the scale of a whole flight. The good judgment lived earlier, at Altoona, at the wisps, at the sagging curtain, and it is all still available on the other branches. The honest move now is the one this ending's silence at dinner is circling: tell the story straight, to Coop, to the logbook, to an instructor, and let the fear finish its work before the fading starts.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Getting away with it and getting it right are different events that feel identical from the inside. Only one of them repeats safely. Label tonight correctly before your memory does it for you.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
