:: End_Spiral [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: 174 seconds"])>>

<<if $pathArray.includes("Hunted onward at two hundred feet")>>The pasture's valley narrows, the mist thickens, and the clear air under the cloud goes from two hundred feet to one hundred to a suggestion. The climb, when it finally can't be refused, happens into full cloud with the airspeed already unsettled.<<else>>The correction your body demanded feels, for four full seconds, like the airplane coming right.<</if>> The attitude indicator shows a bank you don't feel, steepening. The airspeed builds. The altimeter begins to unwind, slowly, then not slowly, and the sound of the airframe changes to a note you have never heard an airplane make.

Radar records the rest with its usual patience: a right turn tightening through three revolutions, altitude trading for airspeed at an accelerating exchange, the last return at 2,700 feet in terrain that reaches 2,600. The wreckage path through the treetops is short. The recorded weather at the nearest station, for the report's purposes: ceiling overcast, visibility four, mist.

The NTSB's probable cause will run twenty-eight words. The docket's most-read document, as always, will be the last radar plot, studied late at night by pilots trying to find the moment it was still recoverable. It is earlier than any of them think. It always is.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>Continued VFR flight into instrument conditions, followed by spatial disorientation and an uncontrolled descent: the general aviation accident report so common its template needs only names and dates. From cloud entry to the last radar return: just under three minutes, a figure so consistent across these accidents that a famous training film simply used it as a title.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The vestibular system cannot fly an airplane, and in cloud it actively prevents an untrained pilot from doing so: every sensation it reports after the first minute is generated by fluid physics, not by the airplane. Overcoming it requires an instrument scan practiced to reflex, which is precisely the skill a VFR pilot lacks by definition. This ending was therefore never going to be decided in the cloud. It was decided in the chain that led there: <<print $badchoices>> choices, each with a reasonable voice attached, each individually survivable, none individually fatal. The cloud only collected.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Every other ending in this scenario, and one habit above all: pre-committing, on the ground, in specific words, to what ends the flight, because the pilot at the kitchen table is the only version of you guaranteed to be flying on instruments that work. The confession frequency was available until roughly the final ninety seconds. The 180 was available for hours. The car was available all day.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The turn this scenario is named for has one requirement: it must be flown while you still believe you don't need it. After that, it stops being a turn and becomes a wish.</p>
</div>
